@node GENERAL "General remarks"

  The following remarks are valid for all API, since every single one
  interacts with some InstallerNG internals.

  - every external resource (GUI, compiler module or function plugin) comes
    as a system shared library with a defined minimal set of functions (which
    may expand in future!)

  - For more convinience you may use the functions of the savage.lib,
    which provides some memory, file and tools functions. Especially the
    sav_AllocMem(), sav_ReadFile2() or sav_StringF2() functions allocate
    memory, which then gets freed by the InstallerNG, so you dont need to
    care for it.

  @{b}Global environment@{ub}

  @{b}Local environment@{ub}

  @{b}Symbol table@{ub}

  @{b}Syntax trees@{ub}

@endnode
@node GUI "GUI API"

  This API is the largest one; since the InstallerNG is a very GUI oriented
  application, there are a bunch of functions to implement. So for every
  single thing, which can happen to the GUI (visible or even not), there
  exists a related function. There are functions for GUI internal event
  handling, for modifying the GUI or even to initialize or free it.

  @{b}Location@{ub}
    libs:installerng/gui/gui.library

  @{b}Implementation@{ub}

@endnode
@node FUNPLUGINS "Function plugins"

  Whenever the InstallerNG interprets a CALL-PLUGIN function, it tries to
  open the related library in a certain version. It then asks for the
  argument types and return types of this plugin and verifies the types
  with the runtime types of the arguments in the script. If this check
  is successful, it calls the function itself and gives some environment
  information and the arguments in a structure to the function.

  Please note that the InstallerNG does not (yet?) cache the plugins. That
  means, it opens, executes and closes the plugin everytime a CALL-PLUGIN
  is executed. Since a plugin is a simple shared library, the AmigaOS caches
  it as long as you dont call the FLUSHLIBS function. The advantage is that
  your script may use custom plugins and can MAKEASSIGN them at the beginning
  of the script.

  @{b}Location@{ub}
    libs:installerng/functionplugins/*

  @{b}Implementation@{ub}

@endnode
@node COMPMODULES "Compiler modules"

  After a successful compilation of the script, the InstallerNG executes some
  modules (if found). Every module has its dedicated priority and the InstallerNG
  arranges the modules with respect to this priority and then executes one after
  the other. The obvious advantage is that one could write some typecheckers and
  optimizers first (at high priority) and perform some modifications on the
  program and then create target code (maybe asm or even C or E or whatever) from
  the tree.

  @{b}Location@{ub}
    libs:installerng/compilermodules/*

  @{b}Implementation@{ub}

@endnode




